[1] Global update (WPV1 ES Pakistan, cVDPV2 Afghanistan, DR Congo, cVDPV1 Yemen) - GPEI/WHO
Date: Thu 8 Jul 2021
Source: Global Polio Eradication Initiative / WHO [edited]
https://polioeradication.org/polio-today/polio-now/this-week/


Poliovirus Weekly Update 7 Jul 2021, World Health Organization
------------------------------------------------------
New wild poliovirus isolates reported this week:
AFP cases: 0
Environment: 1
Others: 0

New cVDPV isolates reported this week:
AFP cases: 3
Environment: 0
Others: 0

Summary of new WPV and cVDPV this week (AFP cases and ES positives):
- Pakistan: 1 WPV1 positive environmental sample
- Afghanistan: 1 cVDPV2 case
- DR Congo: 1 cVDPV2 case
- Yemen: 1 cVDPV1 case

Afghanistan
- No wild poliovirus type 1 (WPV1) case was reported this week. There is 1 case reported in 2021 while the total number of 2020 cases remains at 56.
- 1 case of circulating vaccine-derived poliovirus type 2 (cVDPV2) was reported in Badghis bringing the number of 2021 cases to 42. There were 308 cVDPV2 cases reported in 2020.

Pakistan
- No wild poliovirus type 1 (WPV1) case was reported this week. There is 1 case reported in 2021. The total number of 2020 cases remains at 84.
- 1 WPV1 positive environmental sample was reported in KPTD.
- No case of circulating vaccine-derived poliovirus type 2 (cVDPV2) was reported this week. The number of 2021 cases remains at 8. There were 135 cases reported in 2020.

Angola
- No case of circulating vaccine-derived poliovirus type 2 (cVDPV2) was reported this week. There were 3 cVDPV2 cases reported in 2020.

Benin
- No case of circulating vaccine-derived poliovirus type 2 (cVDPV2) was reported this week. There are 2 cases reported in 2021 so far. There were 3 cVDPV2 cases reported in 2020. These cases are all linked to the Jigawa outbreak in Nigeria.

Burkina Faso
- No case of circulating vaccine-derived poliovirus type 2 (cVDPV2) was reported this week. There is 1 case reported in 2021 so far. The number of 2020 cases remains 65. The country is affected by different outbreaks, 1 linked to the Jigawa outbreak in Nigeria and 1 to the Savanes outbreak in Togo.

Cameroon
- No case of circulating vaccine-derived poliovirus type 2 (cVDPV2) was reported this week. There were 7 cVDPV2 cases reported in 2020.

Central African Republic
- No case of circulating vaccine-derived poliovirus type 2 (cVDPV2) was reported this week. There were 4 cVDPV2 cases reported in 2020.

Chad
- No case of circulating vaccine-derived poliovirus type 2 (cVDPV2) was reported this week. There were 99 cVDPV2 cases reported in 2020 from 3 different outbreaks.
- The risk of further cVDPV2 spread across the Lake Chad subregion remains high.

Congo
- No case of circulating vaccine-derived poliovirus type 2 (cVDPV2) was reported this week. There are 2 cases reported in 2021. There were 2 cases reported in 2020.

Cote d'Ivoire
- No case of circulating vaccine-derived poliovirus type 2 (cVDPV2) was reported this week. The number of 2020 cases remains at 61.

Democratic Republic of the Congo (DR Congo)
- No case of circulating vaccine-derived poliovirus type 2 (cVDPV2) was reported this week. There are 8 cases reported in 2021 so far. The total number of 2020 cases remains at 81.

Egypt
- No cVDPV2 positive environmental sample was reported this week. There are 10 positive samples reported in 2021. There was 1 positive sample reported in 2020.

Ethiopia
- No case of circulating vaccine-derived poliovirus type 2 (cVDPV2) was reported this week. There are 6 cases reported in 2021 so far. The total number of 2020 cases remains at 26.

Ghana
- No case of circulating vaccine-derived poliovirus type 2 (cVDPV2) was reported this week. There were 12 cases reported in 2020.

Guinea
- No case of circulating vaccine-derived poliovirus type 2 (cVDPV2) was reported this week. There are 6 cases in 2021. The total number of 2020 cases remains at 44.

Kenya
- No cVDPV2 positive environmental sample was reported this week. There was 1 cVDPV2 positive environmental sample reported in 2020 and 1 in 2021. The virus is linked to the Banadir outbreak in Somalia.

Liberia
- No case of circulating vaccine-derived poliovirus type 2 (cVDPV2) was reported this week. There are 2 cases in the country.

Madagascar
- No case of circulating vaccine-derived poliovirus type 1 (cVDPV1) was reported this week. There are 4 cases in 2021 and 2 from 2020.

Malaysia
- No case of circulating vaccine-derived poliovirus type 1 (cVDPV1) was reported this week. There was 1 case in 2020.

Mali
- No case of circulating vaccine-derived poliovirus type 2 (cVDPV2) was reported this week. The number of 2020 cases remains at 48.

Niger
- No case of circulating vaccine-derived poliovirus type 2 (cVDPV2) was reported this week. The number of 2020 cases remains at 10.

Nigeria
- No case of circulating vaccine-derived poliovirus type 2 (cVDPV2) was reported this week. The number of 2021 cases remains at 21. There were 8 cases reported in 2020.

Senegal
- No case of circulating vaccine-derived poliovirus type 2 (cVDPV2) was reported this week. The number of 2021 cases remains at 9.

Sierra Leone
- No case of circulating vaccine-derived poliovirus type 2 (cVDPV2) was reported this week. There are 4 cases in 2021 while the number of 2020 cases remains at 10.

Somalia
- No case of circulating vaccine-derived poliovirus type 2 (cVDPV2) was reported this week. There were 14 cVDPV2 cases reported in 2020.

South Sudan
- No case of circulating vaccine-derived poliovirus type 2 (cVDPV2) was reported this week. There are 58 cVDPV2 cases in the country; 8 in 2021 and 50 in 2020.

Sudan
- No case of circulating vaccine-derived poliovirus type 2 (cVDPV2) was reported this week. The number of 2020 cases remains at 58. The initial viruses were linked to the ongoing outbreak in Chad followed by local transmission.

Tajikistan
- No case of circulating vaccine-derived poliovirus type 2 (cVDPV2) was reported this week. The number of 2021 cases remains at 15. There was 1 case reported in 2020.

Togo
- No case of circulating vaccine-derived poliovirus type 2 (cVDPV2) was reported this week. There were 9 cases reported in 2020.

Yemen
- 1 case of circulating vaccine-derived poliovirus type 1 (cVDPV1) was reported in Saadah. There are 3 cases reported in 2021 so far and a total of 35 altogether.

Officially reported WPV1 and cVDPV cases as of 6 Jul 2021
Wild poliovirus (WPV)
- Total global WPV1 cases in 2021: 2 (compared with 81 for the same period in 2020)
- Total global WPV1 cases in 2020: 140

Circulating vaccine-derived poliovirus (cVDPV) cases
- Total global cVDPV cases in 2021: 142 (compared with 183 for the same period in 2020)
- Total global cVDPV cases in 2020: 1093

--
Communicated by:
ProMED
<promed@promedmail.org>

[This week there was a positive environmental sample for WPV1 (wild poliovirus type 1) identified in the Khyber Pakhtunkhwa Tribal Districts. Two weeks ago there was a positive environmental sample identified in Sindh, (Poliomyelitis update (12): global (cVDPV2, WPV1 ES) 20210624.8473119), 2 weeks prior to that, there were 2 positive environmental samples identified in Punjab and Khyber Pukhtunkhwa (Poliomyelitis update (09): global (WPV1 ES, cVDPV2 AFP cases) RFI 20210611.8442001). Interpretation, the absence of AFP (acute flaccid paralysis) cases does not mean there has been interruption of WPV1 transmission in Pakistan. The presence of positive environmental samples means it hasn't occurred as yet, remembering that there is an average of 1 paralytic case for every 200 infected individuals. With respect to cVDPV's (circulating vaccine derived polioviruses), while the weekly reported cases seems to be decreasing, it is not clear that the outbreak transmissions have been interrupted, especially given the delays in confirmation announcements. Highlighting that, cases associated with cVDPVs continue to dominate over cases associated with WPV1.

A map showing the locations of each confirmed case of polio worldwide in the past 12 months can be found at: https://polioeradication.org/polio-today/polio-now/. One sees cases of cVDPV are in a band across Africa and in Afghanistan and Pakistan, cVDPV1 in Madagascar and Yemen, and WPV1 in Afghanistan and Pakistan. - Mod.MPP]

******
[2] Nigeria
Date: Tue 6 Jul 2021
Source: Nigeria Daily Post [edited]
https://dailypost.ng/2021/07/06/outbreak-of-new-polio-type-2-threatens-nigerias-free-status-nigerian-government/


The Federal Government has raised concerns over the recent outbreak of vaccine-derived poliovirus type 2 (cVDPV2) in some parts of the country, just 11 months after being declared free of Wild Polio Virus (WPV) by the Africa Regional Certification Commission for polio eradication (ARCC).

The government said at least 13 states and the Federal Capital Territory have reported the outbreak, including, Abia, Bayelsa, Borno, Delta, FCT, Jigawa, Kano, Kebbi, Lagos, Niger, Rivers, Sokoto, Yobe and Zamfara.

The National Primary Health Care Development Agency, NPHCDA revealed this during a review meeting of the Northern Traditional Leaders Committee on Primary Health Care.

The Executive Director of NPHCDA, Dr. Faisal Shuaib, has now warned that the continuous spread of this virus puts Nigeria's status as a Wild Polio Virus-free nation under threat. Dr. Faisal said the outbreak could have been the result of the large number of children missed during the COVID-19 outbreak response. "This year has been a challenging one due to the COVID-19 pandemic which has affected all areas of our lives including our immunization programme. There are cases of cVDPV2 in some states, hence the need for us as a country to jealously guard our WPV-free status and stop the cVDPV2 transmission in our communities. "We have conducted 4 OBRs [Outbreak Response] using the Novelle Oral Polio Vaccine which is a preferred choice as it doesn't seed the virus [nOPV2]. However, sub-optimal performance has been recorded in all the States due to high number of missed children during the OBR."

Dr. Faisal urged the traditional rulers to maintain their effort of mobilising people for the OBR campaigns and other subsequent rounds of polio vaccination. He asked the traditional leaders to join the call for improved funding of Polio Outbreak Response Campaigns, stressing that donor support in that regard has continued to dwindle. "It is pertinent to state that donor funding for polio has reduced drastically. We will therefore be relying on your influence in advocating to political leaders on the need to continue to fund Polio Outbreak Response campaigns. I also wish to humbly request for your continuous support in mobilising the people for the OBR campaigns and other subsequent rounds of the polio vaccination", he said.

Meanwhile, the Sultan of Sokoto, Sa'adu Abubakar, who spoke on behalf of other traditional rulers said though, certified WPV free, Nigeria's Routine Immunization coverage was still very poor while cases of maternal mortality were still unacceptably high in Northern communities. "It is true, Nigeria is certified Polio Free, however, the reality is Nigeria is not out of the woods as cases of CVDPV2 continue to spread even in states that have been polio-free for nearly 7 years. Added to this, is the scourge of COVID-19 and the challenges of educating our people to create demand and acceptance for vaccines."

[Byline: Chika Onyesi]

